04671nam a22006375i 9780271051314DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152009pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710513147 a10.1515/97802710513142doi  a(DE-B1597)584026  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aDC165b.S53 2009eb 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a944.04/12221 aShapiro, Barry M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTraumatic Politics :bThe Deputies and the King in the Early French Revolution /cBarry M. Shapiro. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2015] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPrologue to Part I -- tIntroduction -- tOne. Arrival in Versailles -- tTwo. The King and His Evil Advisers -- tThree. Defiance at the Jeu de Paume -- tFour. The Royal Session of 23 June -- tFive. The Réunion of 27 June -- tSix. The July Crisis -- tSeven. The Immediate Aftermath of the July Crisis -- tPrologue to Part II -- tIntroduction -- tEight. An Incident at the Abbaye -- tNine. The Passage of the Suspensive Veto -- tTen. Mirabeau and the Exclusion of Deputies from the Ministry -- tEleven. Royal Military Power and the Lingering Effects of Trauma -- tConclusion -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe opening events of the French Revolution have stood as some of the most familiar in modern European history. Traumatic Politics emerges as a fresh voice from the existing historiography of this widely studied course of events. In applying a psychological lens to the classic problem of why the French Revolution's first representative assembly was unable to reach a workable accommodation with Louis XVI, Barry Shapiro contends that some of the key political decisions made by the Constituent Assembly were, in large measure, the product of traumatic reactions to the threats to the lives of its members in the summer of 1789. As a result, Assembly policy frequently reflected a preoccupation with what had happened in the past rather than active engagement with present political realities. In arguing that the manner in which the Assembly dealt with the king bears the imprint of the behavior that typically follows exposure to traumatic events, Shapiro focuses on oscillating periods of traumatic repetition and traumatic denial. Highlighting the historical impact of what could be viewed as a relatively "mild" trauma, he suggests that trauma theory has a much wider field of potential applicability than that previously established by historians, who have generally confined themselves to studying the impact of massively traumatic events such as war and genocide. Moreover, in emphasizing the extent to which monarchical loyalties remained intact on the eve of the Revolution, this book also challenges the widely accepted contention that prerevolutionary cultural and discursive innovations had "desacralized" the king well before 1789.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aLegislatorszFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aPolitical culturezFrancexHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271051314423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271051314.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  